05990nam a22011535i 9780228011590DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280115907 a10.1515/97802280115902doi  a(DE-B1597)657054  a(OCoLC)1323250913  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA441 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a362.1096672231 aWalker, Benjamin Bronnert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligion in Global Health and Development :bThe Case of Twentieth-Century Ghana /cBenjamin Bronnert Walker. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b9 photos, 14 tables, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Colonial Foundations of Global Health: Britain, Gold Coast, and Ghana, 1919–61 -- tReligion and Africanising Health: Ghana, 1957–68 -- tReframing Postcolonial International Health: Ghana, the Netherlands, and West Germany, 1957–90 -- tInternational Health Campaigns and Christian Mission: Ghana, Europe, and North America, 1950–94 -- tPrimary Health Care, Global Health, and Medical Mission: Ghana, the who, and the World Council of Churches, 1960–2000 -- tConclusion: Religion, the Ghanaian State, and the Future of Global Health -- tCatholic Health Services in Ghana, January–April 1982 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe COVID-19 pandemic has made evident that the field of global health – its practices, norms, and failures – has the power to shape the lives of billions. Global health perspectives on the role of religion, however, are strikingly limited. Uncovering the points where religion and global health have connected across the twentieth century, focusing on Ghana, provides an opportunity to challenge narrow approaches.In Religion in Global Health and Development Benjamin Walker shows that the religious features of colonial state architecture were still operating by the turn of the twenty-first century. Walker surveys the establishment of colonial development projects in the twentieth century, with a focus on the period between 1940 and 1990. Crossing the colonial-postcolonial divide, analyzing local contexts in conjunction with the many layers of international organizations, and identifying surprisingly neglected streams of personnel and funding (particularly from Dutch and West German Catholics), this in-depth history offers new ways of conceptualizing global health.Patchworks of international humanitarian intervention, fragmented government services, local communities, and the actions of many foreign powers combined to create health services and the state in Ghana. Religion in Global Health and Development shows that religion and religious actors were critical to this process – socially, culturally, and politically.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity. 0aHealthxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aMedicinexReligious aspects. 0aMissions, MedicalzGhanaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthzGhanaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld healthxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld health. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  a20th.  aAfrica.  aAmerica.  aCanada.  aCatholic.  aChristianity.  aChurches.  aGermany.  aGhana.  aGold Coast.  aKwame Nkrumah.  aMethodism.  aNetherlands.  aPL-480.  aPresbyterian.  aSeventh-day Adventist.  aSwitzerland.  aUSAID.  aUnited States.  aWorld Council.  aaid.  acare.  aclinic.  acolonialism.  adecolonisation.  adevelopment.  adisease.  afood.  aforeign policy.  